The time limit for the submission of tenders shall be 22 August.
Ombudsman: Demagogy on a compulsory health insurance model with additional financial burdens does not pass any criticism to citizens.
Any demagogy of compulsory health insurance, which would impose a direct and high payment burden on citizens, does not withstand any criticism, is considered by the Ombudsman Juris Jansons.
Jansons met today with Health Minister Anda Chakš to discuss the health situation.
After the meeting Jansons told journalists that the industry financing model proposed by the Minister of Health is sustainable and would develop the healthcare system, making it more accessible to patients.
He pointed out, however, that additional funding for healthcare should be mentioned here, as it is currently insufficient.
Jansons also stressed that any demagoguery on compulsory health insurance, which would impose a direct and high payment burden on citizens, does not withstand any criticism, especially when the Dutch model is called upon.
Jansons said that the Netherlands devotes 11% of gross domestic product to health, while Latvia - only 3%.
So the government and the parliament must be sufficiently responsible to understand that this freezing point must rise, said the Ombudsman and added that otherwise the model proposed by the Ministry of Health (VM) would not work.
Čakša thanked the Ombudsman for his support and pointed out that the main concern was that the patient should have access to a doctor, which in turn means that the healthcare system needs additional funding.
The Minister pointed out that with an additional EUR 35 million planned next year it will be possible to do only the most acute cases regarding oncological patients and the remuneration of maternity specialists.
As a result, the VM has drawn up a plan and submitted a request for an additional EUR 41 million in healthcare to reduce the number of teams and investigations.
"The question of priorities, whether it has funds or not," said Chakša.
This amount does not, however, include an increase in salary for doctors.
Commenting on the fact that medical practitioners are not delighted that all three options of the model of healthcare financing are being promoted by the VM for government consideration, including those providing for additional payment to patients, Čakša said that by moving all three models, the government is given the opportunity to choose.
Jansons also added that it is possible to clearly show that Latvia is not prepared to impose additional burdens on the population by moving all three models.
It has already been reported that the VM will defend the variant of the model of financing of health care, which does not provide for an increase in the overall tax burden, however, requires some of the social tax to be shifted to health, says the summary of the conceptual report "On changing the model of financing of the Latvian health care system".
At the same time, the Ministry indicated that the best option for the model of health financing would be chosen as a result of the discussions by the end of September.
