Krasnopjorov and Fadejeva: Lifting a minimum wage - a miracle stick or brake for the economy?
The issue of raising the minimum wage in public debate is almost the status of a sacred cow: either to support raising or to mention some unspeakable, general phrases.
In view of the significant increase in the risk of economic stagnation (as soon as we avoided the technical recession), it is important to stress that raising the minimum wage is not a miracle that will reduce income inequality with one hint, will bring Latvia's wages closer to the Western European level and will fill the state budget.
On the contrary, if the minimum wage is raised too much, it does more harm than good because raising it reduces companies' competitiveness and employment, especially in sectors and low-income regions.
At the first moment, it seems that despite several minimum wage increases during the post-crisis period, the minimum wage in Latvia is not so high that raising the usual few dozens of euros per year would significantly weaken the competitiveness of companies - only 370 euros, while in some European Union (EU) countries the minimum wage is around one and a half thousand.
However, a different picture can be found if we compare it with the average wage in the country (%) – the minimum wage in Latvia (44%) exceeds the EU average.
As the share of the minimum wage recipients in Latvia is significantly higher than in neighbouring countries (in Latvia - 17%, in Lithuania - 11%, in Estonia - 6%[1]), a similar increase in the minimum wage is binding for most companies.
According to the results of the Bank of Latvia survey, each fifth Latvian company replied that increasing the minimum wage at the beginning of 2014, it was important or very important to increase the prices of products.
This means, firstly, that the rise in the minimum wage was partly financed by consumers (i.e. Latvians); secondly, the increase in prices for several companies meant a loss of competitiveness both on the domestic market and abroad (i.e. increased imports and limited exports were encouraged).
Due to weaker competitiveness and stagnant production volumes, it was important for almost every fifteen Latvian companies to lay off employees (which means more unemployment and emigration).
Moreover, almost one in eleven companies replied that it was important for him to limit the recruitment of new employees as a result of raising the minimum wage.
It is worth remembering that in 2011-2013 the minimum wage in Latvia did not change.
Therefore, even if each fifth company noted an important improvement in productivity when assessing the 2014 minimum wage, this does not mean that a similar result could be expected in 2017 (the fourth increase in the minimum wage could in turn outweigh the potential for productivity gains).
Another important result is that, due to the rise in minimum wages, it was also important for several companies to increase the remuneration of employees earning more than minimum wages.
Thus, the effect of the minimum wage was significant even for companies where none of the employees received the minimum wage.
In recent years, the rise in the minimum wage in all three Baltic States has exceeded the increase in nominal labour productivity (real productivity + inflation).
Thus, the further increase in the minimum wage, which is not justified by the increase in labour productivity (even though the overall level of the euro is rather low), will have a negative impact on companies' competitiveness and employment.
When assessing the validity of raising the minimum wage, it is not enough to analyse the economic averages alone.
It is also necessary to assess whether raising the minimum wage is "responsible" in the sectors and regions where the minimum wage is most commonly used.
Results of the Bank of Latvia survey show that the largest concentration of employees with minimum wages is in small enterprises (the number of employees is between 10 and 19; 25%).
At the end of 2013, the share of employees with minimum wages was higher in the industrial and service sectors (16% and 19% respectively) than in the commercial sectors (15%), construction (11%) and financial and insurance sectors (2%).
On the other hand, for Latgale, where the minimum wage is 64% of the average wage (and more than two thirds of the average wage in the private sector), its further increase may be detrimental rather by reducing labour demand (i.e. maintaining already high unemployment) and promoting the sustainability of the shadow economy.
Some signs show that the massive increase in minimum wage implemented in 2014-2015 (by 27%) has slowed the development of Latgale.
For example, Latgale is the only region in Latvia where unemployment was higher in 2015 than in 2013.
It should be noted that there are no regions in Estonia and Lithuania that would be so far behind in terms of average wages from the rest of the country.
For example, in Estonia, the average wage in all regions is at least twice the national minimum wage.
In Lithuania, the lowest wages are in the Tauragė region, but there was also a minimum wage of 54% of the average wage in 2015 (after two rapid increases in the minimum wage in 2016, this figure could reach 58%.
In the public debate, there is a lack of economic justification for raising the minimum wage from time to time up to 68% of the average wage in the country (see, for example, here), and this cannot be achieved either in the short or the long term.
Firstly, there is no EU country with such a high figure from or even close to the average wage.
Secondly, it would mean raising the minimum wage above the average wage in a number of economic sectors (which would mean bankruptcy and mass redundancies of companies in these sectors), such as clothing, leather products, fish processing, catering, and veterinary services; moreover, it is more than the current average wage in Latgale private sector.
The raising of the minimum wage from January 2017 to EUR 400-410 per month, as currently proposed by the Ministry of Welfare, would make the minimum wage in Latvia (% of the average wage) one of the highest in the EU.
If nominal productivity increases by 4%, but minimum wages at least twice as fast, this clearly has negative consequences for companies' competitiveness and employment.
Such negative effects will be most common in sectors and regions where the current minimum wage is often used, for example in Latgale.
The fact that we cannot afford a significant increase in the minimum wage at the moment means that other mechanisms should be used to support low-wage earners.
The immediate effect can be achieved by travelling with a minimum exempt from personal income tax (as far as budget options are concerned).
Insufficient levels of education, inadequate education and poor quality of education acquired, as well as poor health status (often due to the cost of medical treatment and long queues) are mentioned among the real causes of income inequality.
During the survey 521 responses from Latvian company were received regarding the response to the increase in the minimum wage in January 2014.
The survey was conducted within the framework of the Wage Dynamics Network (WDN) project.
These figures represent companies with a workforce of at least 10.
This also explains the low proportion of employees with minimum wages in construction.
