Lourda is going to pick up pilgrims in the shadow of an attack
During the annual Catholic pilgrimage, people gather at the temple of Lourdes Our Lady.
The French security forces are alert, for thousands of Catholics gather at the Lourdes temple on an annual pilgrimage under the shadow of several terrorist acts.
On August 15, each year, tens of thousands of people gather at the temple at the foot of the Pyrenees Mountains for the Festival of Ascension to celebrate the reception of the virgin Mary in heaven.
This year’s pilgrimage takes place at a time when Catholics have been shocked by the murder of an older French priest on July 26, by two Islamic extremists who, during the Mass, invaded the church in the north of France and cut his throat.
The murder of Jacques Amel took place two weeks after a Tunisian -- investigators claim to have radicalized him with Jihadist online video material,-- he was struck by a truck at the party of the Basilian Day celebrations in Nice, Riviera, killing 85 people.
After three large-scale attacks over a period of 18 months, many French citizens are cautious about visiting public events.
The number of tourists fell dramatically, and the authorities were concerned that this year’s pilgrims could fall rapidly.
However, fear of mass withdrawals did not materialize -- and some organizers say that there has even been an influx of visitors' applications at the last moment.
Some 25 000 believers are expected to arrive, including a delegation of large groups from Italy and Belgium and about 200 Christians in the Eastern branch of the Orthodox.
Many pilgrims have declared that they will not be afraid.
"We do not intend to stop living," a 66-year-old visitor Christian said to AFP, describing prayer as the "only weapon" in the fight against violence.
"It's important to show that life continues," said Matthew Guinear - one of the coordinators.
We will not give up our faith, our beliefs, and our way of life simply because some fanatics are trying to sow fear.
Due to concerns about security in France, since the attack in Nice, a number of large-scale measures have been lifted, including the huge market for preserves in the northern town of Lille and the European Cycling Championship, which was due to take place in Nice in September.
"Last week I lived in fear that my phone would call in one call to cancel applications," said Fabien Ležesne last weekend, the priest responsible for the official pilgrimage.
"On the contrary, it seems that the attacks have mobilised believers," he said and announced the influx of last-minute applications.
Christian Gel, head of the trade association of local hotel employees, confirmed "increased interest" in pilgrimage after attacks.
There were extremely strict security measures around the holy place where the virgin Mary appeared to the poor shepherd Bernadet Subir in 1858.
Some 250 police officers and two dozen soldiers have been assigned to protect the site, including bomb neutralisation experts and explosive detection dogs experts.
As the pilgrims passed through security barriers, bags were checked at the entrance, and the number of access points was reduced from twelve to three.
Catherine Simcox, who traveled from northeast England to Lourdes at the beginning of this month, described the enhanced security measures.
"Until Thursday morning there were armed guards in the temples, and then only one entry through the gates (with metal barriers) was possible, as well as bags were searched," said The Local.
"This whole thing scared my three children, who are used to Lourdes, and it was hard not to scare them when they asked why it happened," she said.
It has not damaged my impressions, but it saddened me that it was necessary, and I realized that many people were calmed down by these events.
The Friday opening procession route is also shortened - instead of starting in Lourdes city and moving further to the temple, it will begin and end in the temple.
Other measures include the closure of the airspace for flights over Lourdes, the closure of the streets near the traffic temple and the replacement of waste caves for transparent plastic bags.
Minister of the Interior of France Bernar Kazenev will examine security measures on Saturday.
Some six million people travel to Lourdes each year, making it one of the world’s largest Catholic pilgrimage destinations.
Many visitors lead relatives who are sick or disabled and who come to swim in a cave where Bernadette had seen Mary, believing in the therapeutic properties of water.
Thierry Castio, one of the organizers, described this year's gathering as "a little unusual" in view of "the threat that the roots seem to be found in France."
However, he claimed that this would not affect the quality and depth of their experience.
François, a 58 - year - old volunteer who helped sick pilgrims, admitted that she felt that the presence of soldiers dressed in civilian clothing was "a little depressing."
However, if it calms everyone down, it is good.
